# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: in-context-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:in-context-learning/few-shot-learning] The limiting case of few-shot learning is zero-shot learning that requires no training on examples of the class to be classified; instead, the classification task must be generalized from examples of other classes.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Generative AI applications like large language models (LLM) are common examples of foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Building foundation models is often highly resource-intensive, with the most advanced models costing hundreds of millions of dollars to cover the expenses of acquiring, curating, and processing massive datasets, as well as the compute power required for training.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] These costs stem from the need for sophisticated infrastructure, extended training times, and advanced hardware, such as GPUs.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In contrast, adapting an existing foundation model for a specific task or using it directly is far less costly, as it uses pre-trained capabilities and typically requires only fine-tuning on smaller, task-specific datasets.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Early examples of foundation models are language models like OpenAI's GPT series and Google's BERT.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Beyond text, foundation models have been developed across a range of modalities—including DALL-E, Stable diffusion, and Flamingo for images, MusicGen and LLark for music, and RT-2 for robotic control.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are also being developed for fields like astronomy, radiology, ophthalmology, genomics, coding, time series forecasting, mathematics, and chemistry.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The term vision-language model (VLM) is also used as a near-synonym.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] As governments regulate foundation models, new legal definitions have emerged.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The United States's definitions are the only ones to make reference to the size of a foundation model, and differ on magnitude.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Beyer and Eshoo's definition also specifies that foundation models must achieve a level of performance as to be a potential danger.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In contrast, the E.U. definition requires the model to be designed for generality of output.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] All definitions agree that foundation models must be trained on a broad range of data with potential applications in many domains.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Technologically, foundation models are built using established machine learning techniques like deep neural networks, transfer learning, and self-supervised learning.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models differ from previous techniques as they are general purpose models that function as a reusable infrastructure, instead of bespoke and one-off task-specific models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Advances in computer parallelism (e.g., CUDA GPUs) and new developments in neural network architecture (e.g., Transformers), and the increased use of training data with minimal supervision all contributed to the rise of foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models began to materialize as the latest wave of deep learning models in the late 2010s.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Relative to most prior work on deep learning, these language models demonstrated the potential of training on much larger web-sourced datasets using self-supervised objectives (e.g. predicting the next word in a large corpus of text).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] These approaches, which draw upon earlier works like word2vec and GloVe, deviated from prior supervised approaches that required annotated data (e.g. crowd-sourced labels).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The 2022 releases of Stable Diffusion and ChatGPT (initially powered by the GPT-3.5 model) led to foundation models and generative AI entering widespread public discourse.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Further, releases of LLaMA, Llama 2, and Mistral in 2023 contributed to a greater emphasis placed on how foundation models are released with open foundation models garnering a lot of support and scrutiny.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] As foundation models continue to improve, some AI researchers speculate that almost all next-generation foundation models will be considered frontier models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Since the concept of dangerous capabilities is inherently subjective, there is no strict designation for what foundation models qualify as frontier models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The U.S. definition (via the AI Safety Institute at NIST) tied "frontier" status also to the compute technical threshold to create objective legal requirements.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Due to frontier models' unique capabilities, it is difficult to effectively regulate their development and deployment.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Because of their emergent nature, new dangerous capabilities can appear on their own in frontier models, both in the development stage and after being deployed.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Additionally, since frontier models continue to adapt after deployment, it remains difficult to mitigate all harms that arise from already-deployed models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] If a frontier model happens to be open-source or is released online, the model can also disseminate rapidly, further hampering regulators by creating a lack of accountability.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In response, groups such as the Frontier Model Forum, founded by OpenAI, Anthropic, Google and Microsoft, were created to create safety standards for these advanced foundational models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] A global network of governmental and intergovernmental bodies has emerged to create formal safety standards, including the Global Network of AI Safety Institutes (AISIs) and the G7"Hiroshima AI Process" (HAIP).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Due to their adaptability to a wide range of use-cases, foundation models are sometimes considered to be examples of general-purpose AI.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In designing the EU AI Act, the European Parliament has stated that a new wave of general-purpose AI technologies shapes the overall AI ecosystem.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The fuller structure of the ecosystem, in addition to the properties of specific general-purpose AI systems, influences the design of AI policy and research.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] General-purpose AI systems also often appear in people's everyday lives through applications and tools like ChatGPT or DALL-E.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Government agencies like EU Parliament have identified regulation of general-purpose AI, such as foundation models, to be a high priority.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] General-purpose AI systems are often characterized by large size, opacity, and potential for emergence, all of which can create unintended harms.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Such systems also heavily influence downstream applications, which further exacerbates the need for regulation.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In regards to prominent legislation, a number of stakeholders have pushed for the EU AI Act to include restrictions on general-purpose AI systems, all of which would also apply to foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] World models are sometimes described as foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] World models are a representation of an environment intended to predict the state of that environment after taking a set of actions, as well as to implicitly model physical concepts such as gravity.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Input prompts for world models can include text or images, as well as videos or 3D scenes, and the resulting 3D environments can be exported.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] World models, alongside embodied AI, multi-agent models, and neuroscience models of the brain, are seen as alternatives to large language models for achieving general artificial intelligence.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] World models do not have a fully agreed definition, but have been divided into two scopes: one for representing and understanding the current environment, and another for predicting the future state of that environment.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In the former view, world models are developed using model-based reinforcement learning and a Markov decision process, using model predictive control or Monte Carlo tree search to create policies.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] With the latter, (multimodal) large language models or video generation models can be used.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In addition, these environments can be immersive simulations for training AI agents that can interact in the real world.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] They suggested that agents trained on world models in environments that simulate reality could be applied to real world settings.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In 2022, Yann LeCun saw a world model (defined by him as a neural network that acts as a mental model for aspects of the world that are seen as relevant) as part of a larger system of cognitive architecture – other neural networks that are analogous to different regions of the brain.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In his view, this framework could lead to commonsense reasoning.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] LeCun has estimated that world models would be fully functional by the late 2020s to mid 2030s.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] World models are trained on a variety of data modalities, including text, images, audio and video, and have been applied to video generation.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] One open source dataset for world models includes 1 billion data points across multiple modalities (text, images, audio, video and point clouds), including 1 million manual annotations.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Google DeepMind has also released two world models in two-dimensional space and three-dimensional space, respectively, that were trained on video data, with Google claiming that the latter can be a training environment for AI agents.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Meta released a world model in June 2025, Tencent released an open source world model in July 2025.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Niantic, Inc. spinoff, Niantic Spatial, is developing a world model using anonymized player scans from Pokémon GO.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Other companies that are planning as of 2025 to build world models include ByteDance and xAI.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Fei-Fei Li views world models as applying to robotics and creative works.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Due to the complexity of these models, she advocates for more complex strategies in data acquisition, data engineering, data processing, and synthesizing data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] She co-founded a startup on building world models, which, as of 2024, planned to do so in three phases: incorporating an understanding of three-dimensional space along with time; support for augmented reality; and support for robotics.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Her startup, World Labs, released its commercial world model, Marble, in November 2025.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] World models are intended for use in interactive media (such as video games and movies) and environment simulation.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Proposed use cases for world models include action planning and outcome prediction.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Other applications include social simulacra to simulate social systems.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] *Wired* compared world models to the metaverse, while *Business Insider* noted possible military applications.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In 2025, world models are being applied to drone warfare, robotics, and self-driving vehicles.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] *The Wall Street Journal* speculated that world models could improve spatial reasoning of artificial intelligence models and successfully automate both blue-collar and white-collar jobs.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] As of October 2025, research has shown mixed results in the spatial reasoning capabilities of text-to-video models (in particular, Veo 3).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Creative professionals have expressed concern that world models could disrupt jobs in their industries.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Other concerns include data privacy, simulation of harmful situations, misinformation and disinformation, emergent behaviors, and copyright.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] For a foundation model to effectively generalize, it must acquire rich representations of the training data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] As a result, expressive model architectures that efficiently process large-scale data are often preferred in building foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Currently, the Transformer architecture is the de facto choice for building foundation models across a range of modalities.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are built by optimizing a loss function, which is a mathematical function that determines how model parameters are updated based on model predictions on training data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Language models are often trained with a next-tokens prediction objective, which refers to the extent at which the model is able to predict the next token in a sequence.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Image models are commonly trained with contrastive learning or diffusion training objectives.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] For contrastive learning, images are randomly augmented before being evaluated on the resulting similarity of the model's representations.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] For diffusion models, images are noised and the model learns to gradually de-noise via the objective.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Multimodal training objectives also exist, with some separating images and text during training, while others examine them concurrently.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In general, the training objectives for foundation models promote the learning of broadly useful representations of data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] With the rise of foundation models and the larger datasets that power them, a training objective must be able to parse through internet-scale data for meaningful data points.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Additionally, since foundation models are designed to solve a general range of tasks, training objectives ought to be *domain complete*, or able to solve a broad set of downstream capabilities within the given domain.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Lastly, foundation model training objectives should seek to scale well and be computationally efficient.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] With model size and compute power both being relevant constraints, a training objective must be able to overcome such bottlenecks.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are trained on a large quantity of data, working under the maxim "the more data, the better." Performance evaluation does show that more data generally leads to better performance, but other issues arise as data quantity grows.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Tasks like managing the dataset, integrating data across new applications, ensuring adherence to data licenses, and maintaining data quality all become more difficult as data size grows.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The specific demands of foundation models have only exacerbated such issues, as it remains the norm for large foundation models to use public web-scraped data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models include also search engines data and SEO meta tags data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Public web data remains a plentiful resource, but it also demands stringent moderation and data processing from foundation model developers before it can be successfully integrated into the training pipeline.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Training foundation models often runs the risk of violating user privacy, as private data can be disclosed, collected, or used in ways beyond the stated scope.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Even if no private data is leaked, models can still inadvertently compromise security through learned behavior in the resulting foundation model.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Data quality is another key point, as web-scraped data frequently contains biased, duplicate, and toxic material.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Once foundation models are deployed, ensuring high-quality data is still an issue, as undesirable behavior can still emerge from small subsets of data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The size of foundation models also brings about issues with the computer systems they run on.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The average foundation model is too large to be run within a single accelerator's memory and the initial training process requires an expensive amount of resources.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Such issues are predicted to further exacerbate in future as foundation models grow to new heights.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Due to this constraint, researchers have begun looking into compressing model size through tight model inference.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] GPUs are the most common choice of compute hardware for machine learning, due to high memory storage and strong power.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Typical foundation model training requires many GPUs in a distributed computing setup, connected in parallel with fast interconnects.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Acquiring a sufficient amount of GPUs of requisite compute efficiency is a challenge for many foundation model developers, one that has led to an increasing dilemma in the field.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Larger models require greater compute power, but often at the cost of improved compute efficiency.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Since training remains time-consuming and expensive, the tradeoff between compute power and compute efficiency has led only a few select companies to afford the production costs for large, state of the art foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Some techniques like compression and distillation can make inference more affordable, but they fail to completely shore up this weakness.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The accuracy and capabilities of foundation models often scale predictably with the size of the model and the amount of the training data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Specifically, scaling laws have been discovered, which are data-based empirical trends that relate resources (data, model size, compute usage) to model capabilities.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Particularly, a model's scale is defined by compute, dataset size, and the number of parameters, all of which exhibit a power-law relationship with end performance.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] However, broken scaling laws have been discovered in which this relationship smoothly transitions (at points referred to as break(s)) from a power law with one exponent to a power law with another (different) exponent.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] When one does not collect any points near (or after) the break(s), it can be difficult to obtain an accurate extrapolation.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models are inherently multi-purpose: to use these model for a specific use case requires some form of adaptation.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] At a minimum, models need to be adapted to perform the task of interest (task specification), but often better performance can be achieved by more extensive adaptation to the domain of interest (domain specialization).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] A variety of methods (e.g. prompting, in-context learning, fine-tuning, LoRA) provide different tradeoffs between the costs of adaptation and the extent to which models are specialized.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Some major facets to consider when adapting a foundation model are compute budget and data availability.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models can be very large, up to trillions of parameters in size, so adapting the entirety of a foundation model can be computationally expensive.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Therefore, developers sometimes adapt only the last neural layer or only the bias vectors to save time and space.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] For particularly niche applications, specific data may also not be available to adapt the foundation model sufficiently.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In such circumstances, data must be manually labeled, which is costly and can demand expert knowledge.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Evaluation is a key part of developing foundation models.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Not only does evaluation allow for tracking progress of high-performance models, it also creates benchmarks for future model development.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Stakeholders rely on evaluations to understand model behaviors and gain insight into their various attributes.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Traditionally, foundation models are evaluated relative to each other through standardized task benchmarks like MMLU, MMMU, HumanEval, and GSM8K.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Given that foundation models are multi-purpose, increasingly meta-benchmarks are developed that aggregate different underlying benchmarks.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Examples include LM-Harness, BIG-Bench, HELM, OpenLLM Leaderboard, DecodingTrust, and HEIM.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Since foundation models' utility depends on their own general capabilities and the performance of fine-tuned applications, evaluation must cover both metrics.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Proper evaluation examines both a foundation model's downstream applications in aggregate and the direct properties the foundation model holds.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] To ensure further equity in evaluation, certain existing evaluation frameworks account for all adaptation resources, which leads to more informed analyses for the benefit of all stakeholders.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models' general capabilities allow them to fulfill a unique role in the AI ecosystem, fueled by many upstream and downstream technologies.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Training a foundation model requires several resources (e.g. data, compute, labor, hardware, code), with foundation models often involving immense amounts of data and compute (also referred to as computational power).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Due to foundation models' large development costs and inexpensive adaptation requirements, the AI landscape has shifted to a small subset of AI companies making foundation models for downstream adaptation.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Thus, most foundation model companies outsource this step to specialized data providers (e.g.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Scale AI, Surge) and compute providers (e.g.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Amazon Bedrock, Google Cloud, Microsoft Azure).
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The foundation model developer itself will then take the data and use the supplied compute to actually train the foundation model.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] After the foundation model is completely built, much of the data and labor requirements abate.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In this development process, hardware and compute are the most necessary, and also the most exclusive resources.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] To train larger and more complex AI, a sufficient amount of compute is key.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] However, compute is consolidated in the hands of a few, select entities, which most foundation model developers depend on.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] As such, the foundation model pipeline is concentrated heavily around these providers.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Compute is also costly; in 2023, AI companies spent more than 80% of total capital on compute resources.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Foundation models require a large amount of general data to power their capabilities.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Early foundation models scraped from subsets of the internet to provide this data information.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] As the size and scope of foundation models grows, larger quantities of internet scraping becomes necessary, resulting in higher likelihoods of biased or toxic data.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] This toxic or biased data can disproportionately harm marginalized groups and exacerbate existing prejudices.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] To address this issue of low-quality data that arose with unsupervised training, some foundation model developers have turned to manual filtering.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] This practice, known as data labor, comes with its own host of issues.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Such manual data detoxification is often outsourced to reduce labor costs, with some workers making less than $2 per hour.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The foundation model will then be hosted online either via the developer or via an external organization.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Once released, other parties can create applications based on the foundation model, whether through fine-tuning or wholly new purposes.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] People can then access these applications to serve their various means, allowing one foundation model to power and reach a wide audience.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] After a foundation model is built, it can be released in one of many ways.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] There are many facets to a release: the asset itself, who has access, how access changes over time, and the conditions on use.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] All these factors contribute to how a foundation model will affect downstream applications.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] In particular, the two most common forms of foundation model release are through APIs and direct model downloads.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] When a model is released via an API, users can query the model and receive responses, but cannot directly access the model itself.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Comparatively, the model could be directly downloadable for users to access and modify.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Both release strategies are often classified as an open release.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] The exact definition of an open release is disputed, but widely accepted requirements are provided by the Open Source Initiative.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Some open foundation models are: PaLM 2, Llama 2, Granite, and Mistral.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] While open foundation models can further research and development more easily, they are also more susceptible to misuse.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Open foundation models can be downloaded by anyone, and particularly powerful models can be fine-tuned to intentionally or unintentionally cause harm.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] During a closed release, the foundation model cannot be accessed by the public, but is used internally by an organization.
[src:in-context-learning/foundation-model] Such releases are considered safer, but offer no additional value to the research community or the public at large.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] It can also be defined as the practice of designing and refining input instructions given to a generative AI model to produce more accurate, relevant, or useful outputs.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Effective prompt engineering involves understanding how a model interprets language, and may include techniques such as few-shot prompting, chain-of-thought prompting, and role assignment.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] It is increasingly considered a skill for working with large language models (LLMs) in both research and professional contexts.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] During the 2020s AI boom, prompt engineering became regarded as a business capability across corporations and industries.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Employees with the title **prompt engineer** were hired to create prompts that would increase productivity and efficacy, although the individual title has since lost traction amid AI models that produce better prompts than humans and corporate training in prompting for general employees.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Common prompting techniques include multi-shot, chain-of-thought, and tree-of-thought prompting, as well as assigning roles to the model.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Automated prompt generation methods, such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), provide for greater accuracy and a wider scope of functions for prompt engineers.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt injection is a type of cybersecurity attack that targets machine learning models through malicious prompts.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt is some natural language text that describes and prescribes the task that an artificial intelligence (AI) should perform.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt for a text-to-text language model can be a query, a command, or a longer statement referencing context, instructions, and conversation history.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The process of prompt engineering may involve designing clear queries, refining wording, providing relevant context, specifying the style of output, and assigning a character for the AI to mimic in order to guide the model toward more accurate, useful, and consistent responses.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] When communicating with a text-to-image or a text-to-audio model, a typical prompt contains a description of a desired output such as "a high-quality photo of an astronaut riding a horse" or "Lo-fi slow BPM electro chill with organic samples".
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt engineering may be applied to text-to-image models to achieve a desired subject, style, layout, lighting, and aesthetic.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Common terms used to describe various specific prompt engineering techniques include *chain-of-thought*, *tree-of-thought*, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A 2024 survey of the field identified over 50 distinct text-based prompting techniques, 40 multimodal variants, and a vocabulary of 33 terms used across prompting research, highlighting a present lack of standardised terminology for prompt engineering.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Vibe coding is an AI-assisted software development method where a user prompts an LLM with a description of what they want and lets it generate or edit the code.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In 2025, "vibe coding" was the Collins Dictionary word of the year.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Context engineering is a related process that focuses on the context elements that accompany user prompts, which include system instructions, retrieved knowledge, tool definitions, conversation summaries, and task metadata.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Context engineering is performed to improve reliability, provenance and token efficiency in production LLM systems.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The concept emphasises operational practices such as token budgeting, provenance tags, versioning of context artifacts, observability (logging which context was supplied), and context regression tests to ensure that changes to supplied context do not silently alter system behaviour.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Research has found that the performance of large language models (LLMs) is highly sensitive to choices such as the ordering of examples, the quality of demonstration labels, and even small variations in phrasing.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In some cases, reordering examples in a prompt produced accuracy shifts of more than 40 percent.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A model's ability to temporarily learn from prompts is known as *in-context learning*.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In-context learning is an emergent ability of large language models.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] It is an emergent property of model scale, meaning that breaks in scaling laws occur, leading to its efficacy increasing at a different rate in larger models than in smaller models.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Unlike training and fine-tuning, which produce lasting changes, in-context learning is temporary.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Training models to perform in-context learning can be viewed as a form of meta-learning, or "learning to learn".
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Research consistently demonstrates that LLMs are highly sensitive to subtle variations in prompt formatting, structure, and linguistic properties.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Some studies have shown up to 76 accuracy points across formatting changes in few-shot settings.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Linguistic features significantly influence prompt effectiveness—such as morphology, syntax, and lexico-semantic changes—which meaningfully enhance task performance across a variety of tasks.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Clausal syntax, for example, improves consistency and reduces uncertainty in knowledge retrieval.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] This sensitivity persists even with larger model sizes, additional few-shot examples, or instruction tuning.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] To address sensitivity of models and make them more robust, several evaluative methods have been proposed.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] FormatSpread facilitates systematic analysis by evaluating a range of plausible prompt formats, offering a more comprehensive performance interval.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Similarly, PromptEval estimates performance distributions across diverse prompts, enabling robust metrics such as performance quantiles and accurate evaluations under constrained budgets.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt may include a few examples for a model to learn from in-context, an implementation of few-shot learning for LLMs.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] It is possible to fine-tune models on CoT reasoning datasets to enhance this capability further and stimulate better interpretability.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] As originally proposed by Google, each CoT prompt is accompanied by a set of input/output examples—called *exemplars*—to demonstrate the desired model output, making it a few-shot prompting technique.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] However, according to a later paper from researchers at Google and the University of Tokyo, simply appending the words "Let's think step-by-step" was also effective, which allowed for CoT to be employed as a zero-shot technique.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In 2022, text-to-image models like DALL-E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney were released to the public.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] These models take text prompts as input and use them to generate images.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Early text-to-image models typically do not understand negation, grammar and sentence structure in the same way as large language models, and may thus require a different set of prompting techniques.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The prompt "a party with no cake" may produce an image including a cake.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A text-to-image prompt commonly includes a description of the subject of the art, the desired medium (such as *digital painting* or *photography*), style (such as *hyperrealistic* or *pop-art*), lighting (such as *rim lighting* or *crepuscular rays*), color, and texture.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Word order also affects the output of a text-to-image prompt.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Words closer to the start of a prompt may be emphasized more heavily.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Some text-to-image models are capable of imitating the style of particular artists by name.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] For example, the phrase *in the style of Greg Rutkowski* has been used in Stable Diffusion and Midjourney prompts to generate images in the distinctive style of Polish digital artist Greg Rutkowski.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Famous artists such as Vincent van Gogh and Salvador Dalí have also been used for styling and testing.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] For text-to-image models, *textual inversion* performs an optimization process to create a new word embedding based on a set of example images.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] This embedding vector acts as a "pseudo-word" which can be included in a prompt to express the content or style of the examples.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In 2023, Meta's AI research released Segment Anything, a computer vision model that can perform image segmentation by prompting.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] As an alternative to text prompts, Segment Anything can accept bounding boxes, segmentation masks, and foreground/background points.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The process of writing and refining a prompt for an LLM or generative AI shares some parallels with an iterative engineering design process, such as by discovering reusable best practices through reproducible experimentation.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] However, several fundamental limitations constrain its reliability as a discipline.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Effective prompting strategies are highly model specific, a technique that improves performance on one model may degrade it on another, making generalization difficult.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Prompts are also brittle: minor surface-level changes in phrasing, punctuation, or word order can produce dramatically different outputs, even when the semantic intent remains identical.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] This instability makes it difficult to establish durable, transferable prompt patterns across deployment contexts.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Furthermore, as AI models continue to improve in their ability to interpret user intent directly, many manual prompting techniques are becoming obsolete.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Advances in instruction-following and model reasoning have reduced the marginal value of elaborate prompt construction for everyday tasks, raising questions about the long-term viability of prompt engineering as a standalone discipline.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Recent research has explored automated prompt engineering, using optimization algorithms to generate or refine prompts without human intervention.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] These automated approaches aim to identify effective prompt patterns by analyzing model gradients, reinforcement feedback, or evolutionary processes, reducing the need for manual experimentation.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Retrieval-augmented generation is a technique that enables GenAI models to retrieve and incorporate new information.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] It modifies interactions with an LLM so that the model responds to user queries with reference to a specified set of documents, using this information to supplement information from its pre-existing training data.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] This allows LLMs to use domain-specific and/or updated information.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] RAG improves large language models by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Unlike traditional LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] By dynamically retrieving information, RAG enables AI to generate more accurate responses and fewer AI hallucinations without frequent retraining.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] GraphRAG (coined by Microsoft Research) is a technique that extends RAG with the use of a knowledge graph to allow the model to connect disparate pieces of information, synthesize insights, and understand summarized semantic concepts over large data collections.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] It was shown to be effective on datasets like the Violent Incident Information from News Articles.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] LLMs themselves can be used to compose prompts for LLMs.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] CoT examples can be generated by LLM themselves.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In "auto-CoT", a library of questions are converted to vectors by a model such as BERT.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Questions close to the centroid of each cluster are selected, in order to have a subset of diverse questions.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] An LLM does zero-shot CoT on each selected question.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The question and the corresponding CoT answer are added to a dataset of demonstrations.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] These diverse demonstrations can then added to prompts for few-shot learning.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In "prefix-tuning", "prompt tuning", or "soft prompting", floating-point vectors are searched directly by gradient descent to maximize the log-likelihood on outputs.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] An earlier result uses the same idea of gradient descent search, but is designed for masked language models like BERT, and searches only over token sequences, rather than numerical vectors.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Formally, it searches for $\arg \max _{\tilde {X}}\sum _{i}\log Pr[Y^{i}|{\tilde {X}}\ast X^{i}]$ where ${\tilde {X}}$ ranges over token sequences of a specified length.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Early precedents of structured user interaction with ruled-based AI systems can be found in enterprise automation software from 1990s.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] For example, The Intelligent Filling Manager (1999), developed by Krishna C.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Mukherjee, used a dynamic Q&A interface driven by rule-based expert system to collect user inputs for generating regulatory filings automatically across jurisdictions.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] While not involving neural networks, such systems featured prompt-like workflows that influenced later human-in-the-loop AI designs.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In 2018, researchers first proposed that all previously separate tasks in natural language processing (NLP) could be cast as question-answer problems over a context.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The AI boom saw an increased focus within academic literature and professional practice on applying prompting techniques to get the model to output the desired outcome and avoid nonsensical output, a process characterized by trial-and-error.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] According to *The Wall Street Journal* in 2025, the job of prompt engineer was one of the hottest in 2023, but has become obsolete due to models that better intuit user intent and to company trainings.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] A repository for prompts reported that over 2,000 public prompts for around 170 datasets were available in February 2022.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In 2022, the *chain-of-thought* prompting technique was proposed by Google researchers.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] In 2023, several text-to-text and text-to-image prompt databases were made publicly available.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] The Personalized Image-Prompt (PIP) dataset, a generated image-text dataset that has been categorized by 3,115 users, has also been made available publicly in 2024.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt injection is a cybersecurity exploit in which adversaries craft inputs that appear legitimate but are designed to cause unintended behavior in machine learning models, particularly large language models.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] This attack takes advantage of the model's inability to distinguish between developer-defined prompts and user inputs, allowing adversaries to bypass safeguards and influence model behaviour.
[src:in-context-learning/in-context-learning] While LLMs are designed to follow trusted instructions, they can be manipulated into carrying out unintended responses through carefully crafted inputs.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] A **language model** is a computational model that predicts sequences in natural language.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Large language models (LLMs), currently their most advanced form as of 2026, are predominantly based on transformers trained on larger datasets (frequently using texts scraped from the public internet).
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] They have superseded recurrent neural network-based models, which had previously superseded the purely statistical models, such as the word *n*-gram language model.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Noam Chomsky did pioneering work on language models in the 1950s by developing a theory of formal grammars.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] In 1980, statistical approaches were explored and found to be more useful for many purposes than rule-based formal grammars.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Discrete representations like word *n*-gram language models, with probabilities for discrete combinations of words, made significant advances.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] In the 2000s, continuous representations for words, such as word embeddings, began to replace discrete representations.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes a word’s meaning such that words closer in vector space are similar in meaning and common relationships between words, such as plurality or gender, are preserved.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] A word *n*-gram language model is a statistical model of language which calculates the probability of the next word in a sequence from a fixed size window of previous words.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] If one previous word is considered, it is a bigram model; if two words, a trigram model; if *n* − 1 words, an *n*-gram model.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Special tokens are introduced to denote the start and end of a sentence $\langle s\rangle$ and $\langle /s\rangle$ .
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] To prevent a zero probability being assigned to unseen words, the probability of each seen word is slightly lowered to make room for the unseen words in a given corpus.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] To achieve this, various smoothing methods are used, from simple "add-one" smoothing (assigning a count of 1 to unseen *n*-grams, as an uninformative prior) to more sophisticated techniques, such as Good–Turing discounting or back-off models.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Word *n-*gram models have largely been superseded by recurrent neural network–based models, which in turn have been superseded by Transformer-based models often referred to as large language models.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Maximum entropy language models encode the relationship between a word and the *n*-gram history using feature functions.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] where $Z(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m-1})$ is the partition function, a is the parameter vector, and $f(w_{1},\ldots ,w_{m})$ is the feature function.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] In the simplest case, the feature function is just an indicator of the presence of a certain *n*-gram.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] It is helpful to use a prior on a or some form of regularization.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] The log-bilinear model is another example of an exponential language model.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Skip-gram language model is an attempt at overcoming the data sparsity problem that the preceding model (i.e. word *n*-gram language model) faced.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Words represented in an embedding vector were not necessarily consecutive anymore, but could leave gaps that are *skipped* over (thus the name "skip-gram").
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Formally, a k-skip-n-gram is a length-n subsequence where the components occur at distance at most k from each other.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] In skip-gram model, semantic relations between words are represented by linear combinations, capturing a form of compositionality.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] where ≈ is made precise by stipulating that its right-hand side must be the nearest neighbor of the value of the left-hand side.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Continuous representations or embeddings of words are produced in recurrent neural network-based language models (known also as *continuous space language models*).
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Such continuous space embeddings help to alleviate the curse of dimensionality, which is the consequence of the number of possible sequences of words increasing exponentially with the size of the vocabulary, further causing a data sparsity problem.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Neural networks avoid this problem by representing words as non-linear combinations of weights in a neural net.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] A large language model (LLM) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Although sometimes matching human performance, it is not clear whether they are plausible cognitive models.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] At least for recurrent neural networks, it has been shown that they sometimes learn patterns that humans do not, but fail to learn patterns that humans typically do.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Evaluation of the quality of language models is mostly done by comparison to human created sample benchmarks created from typical language-oriented tasks.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Other, less established, quality tests examine the intrinsic character of a language model or compare two such models.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Since language models are typically intended to be dynamic and to learn from data they see, some proposed models investigate the rate of learning, e.g., through inspection of learning curves.
[src:in-context-learning/language-model] Various data sets have been developed for use in evaluating language processing systems.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:in-context-learning/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
